/*
LISKOV SUBSTITUTION PRINCIPLE (LSP)

1. Definition

The Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) is the third
principle of the SOLID principles.

It was introduced by Barbara Liskov in 1987.

It states:

"Objects of a superclass should be replaceable
with objects of its subclasses without affecting
the correctness of the program."

In simple words:

A child class should be able to replace its
parent class without causing unexpected behavior.

--------------------------------------------------

2. Why Do We Need LSP?

Inheritance is one of the most important features
of Object-Oriented Programming.

A child class inherits properties and methods
from its parent class.

However, if the child class behaves differently
from what the parent class promises, the program
can produce incorrect results.

LSP ensures that every child class behaves
correctly when used through a parent reference.

--------------------------------------------------

3. Relationship Between OCP And LSP

The Open/Closed Principle (OCP) allows us
to extend software without modifying existing code.

However, OCP works properly only when child classes
can safely replace parent classes.

LSP ensures that subclasses are truly compatible
with their parent classes.

Therefore:

OCP depends on LSP.

Without LSP, OCP cannot be fully achieved.

--------------------------------------------------

4. Banking Application Example

Consider a Banking Application.

The bank provides different account types:

• Savings Account
• Current Account
• Fixed Deposit Account

All account types are represented using
a common Account class.

Initially the design looks correct.

--------------------------------------------------

5. Problem Without LSP

Suppose Account defines:

• deposit()
• withdraw()

Savings Account

Supports:

• deposit()
• withdraw()

Current Account

Supports:

• deposit()
• withdraw()

Fixed Deposit Account

Supports:

• deposit()

Does NOT support:

• withdraw()

--------------------------------------------------

6. Incorrect Design

Account
│
├── SavingsAccount
├── CurrentAccount
└── FixedDepositAccount

Since FixedDepositAccount extends Account,
it is forced to implement withdraw().

Example:

class FixedDepositAccount extends Account
{

    @Override
    public void withdraw()
    {

        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }
}

--------------------------------------------------

7. Why Is This Wrong?

Suppose:

Account account =
        new FixedDepositAccount();

WithdrawalService service =
        new WithdrawalService(account);

service.withdraw();

Runtime Output:

UnsupportedOperationException

The application crashes.

Although FixedDepositAccount is an Account,
it cannot behave like a normal Account.

Therefore it cannot safely replace Account.

Hence LSP is violated.

--------------------------------------------------

8. LSP Definition Explained

According to Barbara Liskov:

If a program works correctly with a parent class,
it should continue to work correctly when any
child class object is substituted.

Example:

Bird bird = new Sparrow();

Bird bird = new Eagle();

Both work correctly.

The child objects can replace Bird safely.

Therefore LSP is satisfied.

--------------------------------------------------

9. Correct LSP Design

Instead of forcing every account to support
withdrawals, create a better hierarchy.

Account
│
├── FixedDepositAccount
│
└── WithdrawableAccount
    │
    ├── SavingsAccount
    └── CurrentAccount

Now:

Account
    -> deposit()

WithdrawableAccount
    -> withdraw()

Only accounts that support withdrawal
inherit WithdrawableAccount.

--------------------------------------------------

10. Benefits Of Correct Design

• No UnsupportedOperationException
• Better inheritance hierarchy
• Better maintainability
• Better scalability
• Better flexibility

--------------------------------------------------

11. How LSP Is Achieved

Parent classes define behaviors that every
child class can actually support.

Child classes must never:

• Remove functionality
• Break functionality
• Change expected behavior

If the parent promises something,
the child must fulfill that promise.

--------------------------------------------------

12. Behavioral Subtyping

LSP is based on the concept of
Behavioral Subtyping.

Behavioral Subtyping means:

A child class should not only inherit methods,
but should also preserve the behavior expected
from those methods.

Example:

Account account =
        new SavingsAccount();

account.withdraw();

Works correctly.

--------------------------------------------------

Account account =
        new CurrentAccount();

account.withdraw();

Works correctly.

--------------------------------------------------

Account account =
        new FixedDepositAccount();

account.withdraw();

Fails.

Therefore FixedDepositAccount is not a
behavioral subtype of Account.

--------------------------------------------------

13. Rules Of LSP

There are several important rules that help
ensure LSP compliance.

--------------------------------------------------

Rule 1: Signature Rule

Child methods should have compatible signatures.

Parameter types should remain compatible.

Return types may become narrower.

--------------------------------------------------

Rule 2: Exception Rule

Child classes should not throw broader exceptions.

Example:

Parent:

public void withdraw()
        throws IOException

Child:

public void withdraw()
        throws FileNotFoundException

Valid.

--------------------------------------------------

Child:

public void withdraw()
        throws Exception

Invalid.

--------------------------------------------------

Rule 3: Invariant Rule

Child classes must preserve parent constraints.

Example:

Car

speed < limit

Every child class must maintain:

speed < limit

--------------------------------------------------

Rule 4: History Constraint

Child classes should not allow state changes
that parent classes do not allow.

Example:

Car mileage can only increase.

A child class must not reset mileage to zero.

--------------------------------------------------

Rule 5: Preconditions

Child classes may weaken preconditions.

Parent:

Valid values:
1 to 5

Child:

Valid values:
1 to 10

Allowed.

--------------------------------------------------

Child:

Valid values:
1 to 3

Not Allowed.

--------------------------------------------------

Rule 6: Postconditions

Child classes may strengthen postconditions.

Parent:

brake()
reduces speed

Child:

brake()
reduces speed
and charges battery

Allowed.

--------------------------------------------------

14. Common LSP Violations

1. Throwing UnsupportedOperationException

Example:

withdraw()
{
    throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
}

--------------------------------------------------

2. Empty Method Implementations

Example:

deleteFile()
{
}

The child cannot support behavior
but still inherits it.

--------------------------------------------------

3. Using instanceof Frequently

Example:

if(account instanceof FixedDepositAccount)
{
}

Frequent instanceof checks often indicate
poor inheritance design.

--------------------------------------------------

4. Returning Constant Values

Example:

public int getFuel()
{
    return 0;
}

Regardless of state,
the method always returns the same value.

This often indicates LSP violation.

--------------------------------------------------

